Y by Adventure10, Mango247SolutionIf we make the substitution $x \to \frac{1}{x}$, then we get $f\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) + \frac{1}{x}f(x) = \frac{1}{x}$.



So then we have the system

\begin{align*}
f(x)+xf\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)&=x\\
 \frac{1}{x}f(x) + f\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) &=\frac{1}{x}
\end{align*}





Multiplying the second relation by $x$ yields $f(x) + xf\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) = 1$. But from the first relation we know that this is $x$, so we must have that $\boxed{x=1}$.



Remark. While that was probably the intended method, in my opinion the question is horribly flawed. I'm not quite sure if it is fixable.

Y by Adventure10, Mango247SolutionOutline:

Use sum of cubes factorization on the first two terms, factor out the $a-c$ and then use Simon's Favorite Factoring Trick.

\begin{align*}
 (a-b)^{3}+(b-c)^{3}+(c-a)^{3}&=(a-c)(a^2+b^2-2ab+b^2+c^2-2bc-ab+ac+b^2-bc)+(c-a)^3 \\
&=(a-c)(a^2+3b^2+c^2-3ab-3bc+ac)-(a-c)^3 \\
&=(a-c)(a^2+3b^2+c^2-3ab-3bc+ac-a^2-c^2+2ac) \\
&=(a-c)(3b^2-3ab-3bc+3ac)\\
&=3(a-c)(b-a)(b-c) \\
&=\boxed{3(a-b)(b-c)(c-a)}
\end{align*}

