Y by The condition implies $\angle CAB = \angle ABE$. However, notice that $\angle EBA = \angle ABD$ due the definition of reflections. Therefore, $\angle BAC = \angle ABC$, so $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles with $BC = 6$. Let $T = \angle BAC$, then $2T = \angle EBC$. By Law of Cosines, we have that

\begin{align*}
6^2 = 3^2 + 6^2 - 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 6 \cdot \cos \left(T\right) \quad \longrightarrow \quad \cos \left(T\right) = \tfrac{1}{4}.
\end{align*}By Angle Bisector Theorem,

\begin{align*}
\dfrac{AB}{BD} = \dfrac{AC}{CD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \dfrac{3}{BD} = \dfrac{6}{CD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \dfrac{3}{BD} = \dfrac{6}{6 - BD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad BD = 2,\text{ }CD = 4. 
\end{align*}Thus, $BE = BD = 2$. Notice, $\sin\left(T\right) = \tfrac{\sqrt{15}}{4}$, so $\cos\left(2T\right) = \cos^2\left(T\right) - \sin^2\left(T\right) = -\tfrac{7}{8}$. By Law of Cosines, we have:

\begin{align*}
CE = \sqrt{BC^2 + BE^2 - 2 \cdot BC \cdot BE \cdot \cos \left(2T\right)} = \sqrt{6^2 + 2^2 - 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 2 \cdot -\tfrac{7}{8}} = \boxed{\sqrt{61}}.
\end{align*}
